<div id="bookReviews">
  




  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section firstReview">
      

<div id="review_928472217" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/928472217" />
    <a title="Robert Duder" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/25398503-robert-duder"><img alt="Robert Duder" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1383855409p2/25398503.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/928472217?book_show_action=true">May 04, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Robert Duder" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Robert Duder" href="/user/show/25398503-robert-duder">Robert Duder</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer928472217" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14462839296502544259">It has been some time since I read a sports drama, in fact I can’t even recall one off the top of my head. This is what drew me to “Story of The Ghost.” If I asked you to find me something that was as much Friday Night Lights as it was Shawshank Redemption or Catcher In The Rye, you would think me crazy. I don’t use those comparisons lightly. Story of The Ghost is a coming of age story in various capacities. Anyone calling it a “sports” novel is missing the boat entirely. This story is so much d</span>
  <span id="freeText14462839296502544259" style="display:none">It has been some time since I read a sports drama, in fact I can’t even recall one off the top of my head. This is what drew me to “Story of The Ghost.” If I asked you to find me something that was as much Friday Night Lights as it was Shawshank Redemption or Catcher In The Rye, you would think me crazy. I don’t use those comparisons lightly. Story of The Ghost is a coming of age story in various capacities. Anyone calling it a “sports” novel is missing the boat entirely. This story is so much deeper, complex and often heart wrenching. In fact, Mahoney’s intensely descriptive style leaves you with a foreboding sadness as you are drawn and sucked into the world surrounding the emotional angst of young Gavin. From the opening of the book in the hot, dry and acrid desert scene of a prison to the similar style of the football field and Gavin’s unquenchable (pun intended) desire to “run”, the story is one of the most multi-layered, intense, forlorn stories I have ever read.<br /><br />Some, I would guess, may find Mahoney’s style of writing almost pretentious but for some readers they welcome sheer intelligence. The same style was indicative of Charles Dickens who went into intense detail of every single aspect whether it be the setting, clothing, emotions of the characters and Mahoney does this unapologetically. Am I saying this is a good style of writing? For some, absolutely! Others will find it overbearing. I found much of the writing very nearly poetic in its delivery and found myself re-reading certain lines or scenes and not because they were hard to follow but rather the style deserves re-reading. To think this is Mahoney’s first novel seems unfathomable because he has a style all his own already. “In a way, I’m glad I don’t know his real name. All I’ve got to do is write the story the way I see it and let it play out in the minds of my readers. Am I lost thinking they can imagine him in the same way that I do? It’s The Ghost on the field by his lonesome where I’m going to start. His aloneness gets me.” – Chapter 25 – SOTG I quote this section because it moved me. Just that small paragraph I read more than once because there was something powerful about it. I’m not even sure Mahoney would realize just how much his flourish makes you stop and take a deep breath.<br /><br />There is nothing I like more as a reader discovering an author for the first time. You start something else when you’ve finished their book and you suddenly find yourself pining for that author’s way of making a story come to life. It wasn’t even the football that touched me, in fact, I felt as though football was a third or fourth thought to this story (not to downplay it because it’s clear Mahoney has a passion for the pigskin) but the depth of angst to the story is truly mind numbing. Whether it is the intention or not I found the story very sad. The entire thing being set against the backdrop of that desert haunts you with each chapter because the setting imitate the characters or vice versa. A casual read Story of The Ghost is not. It isn’t fluff and it isn’t an easy read as I hoped I’ve explained. But that only makes it all the more worthwhile. I fully intend on reading more or Mahoney’s work and I would encourage the most adept readers to do the same. I believe we will be hearing more of him and I hope this work gets the acclaim it deserves.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="14462839296502544259" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

